<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lycium californicum </i>is a spreading, deciduous shrub to 4 m. The clustered, fleshy leaves are glabrous. The flower tube is the length of the calyx. The fruits are red and fleshy, and seed longevity is short (Barton et al. 2016). Plants grow in southern California, including the Channel Islands, coastal San Diego and Los Angeles counties, Arizona, and in Mexico. <i>L. californicum </i>is a CNPS list 4.2 plant.<br/>
<br/>
A mix of coastal shrubs and succulents occur in the stands of this maritime, succulent scrub alliance. Stands are rare on the northern Channel Islands (isolated patches on Santa Rosa Island), and they are relatively more common on the southern Channel Islands. Stands are also scattered on the mainland from Los Angeles County south to Baja California and its islands, as well as Mexico's north and central Gulf Coast. On the islands, a number of rare, threatened or endangered species also occur in this scrub alliance. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance was cited as <i>Lycium californicum</i> Provisional Shrubland Alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
