    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bg-h, Bj). Dunkle (1950) mapped stands on the eastern and western terraces and along sea cliffs of the Channel Islands, and Corry (2006) distinguished between <i>Lycium</i> scrub and <i>Lycium</i>/sea cliff scrub on Santa Barbara Island. Others (Johnson and Rodriguez 2001, HDR 2014b, Junak et al. 2007) described <i>L. californicum</i> stands as maritime succulent scrub on Santa Catalina and San Clemente islands. Stands on the mainland with<i> Euphorbia misera </i>(CNPS list 2.2) and possibly introduced individuals of <i>Agave shawii </i>(CNPS list 2) occupy the coastal bluffs on Point Loma, San Diego Co. Other stands on the mainland include those along the Palos Verdes Peninsula (Verdone and Evens 2010) in Los Angeles Co.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are extremely scattered on the mainland with impacts of development and non-native plants. Stands on the Channel Islands have fluctuated upon European settlement, which brought non-native plants, goats, and rabbits. These animals grazed heavily on native vegetation, restricting shrublands of both <i>Lycium californicum </i>and <i>Coreopsis gigantea </i>to progressively smaller and more isolated patches (Corry 2006). </div>
</div>

    

    

